{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654640","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654640"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:53:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:53:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18624"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18624","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18624"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11356"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78539"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11356","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11356"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18624"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63880"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"10234"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26357"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26362"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26913"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78539","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78539"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMedical terms such as flexion/extension and abduction/adduction have very precise meanings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA physiotherapy student is learning about basic movements of joints in the human body. The student needs to understand the fundamental principles of flexion and extension.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes flexion and extension movements?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Occurrence in the sagittal plane around a mediolateral axis","Occurrence in the frontal plane around an anteroposterior axis","Occurrence in the frontal plane around a vertical axis","Occurrence in multiple planes simultaneously","Occurrence in the transverse plane around a vertical axis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that flexion and extension are \u003Cstrong\u003Emovements that occur in the sagittal plane around a mediolateral axis\u003C/strong\u003E. These movements are fundamental to human motion and are defined relative to the anatomical position. Flexion typically decreases the angle between two body parts, while extension increases this angle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMovements that occur in the frontal plane around an anteroposterior axis\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes abduction and adduction movements\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMovements that occur in the transverse plane around a vertical axis\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes rotation movements\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMovements that occur in multiple planes simultaneously\u003C/strong\u003E - While complex movements may involve multiple planes, pure flexion and extension occur in a single plane\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMovements that occur in the frontal plane around a vertical axis\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not anatomically possible as a primary movement pattern\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the planes and axes of movement is crucial for describing and analysing human motion. The sagittal plane divides the body into right and left portions, and movements in this plane occur around the mediolateral axis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Flexion and extension movements occur in the sagittal plane around a mediolateral axis.","Flexion generally decreases the angle between body parts while extension increases it.","The anatomical position is the reference point for describing flexion and extension movements."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63880"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18624"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63880","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63880"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T12:32:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T12:33:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11356"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78539"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{